\section*{Background}
\label{sec:background}
\raggedright
DHS seeks to incentivize the thoughtful deployment of email authentication technologies and increase the trustworthiness of messages to and from government agencies. These technologies enable a recipient mail server to have reasonable assurance that a message that \textit{purports} to be from a given domain is genuine or not.

This scorecard details the results of .gov-wide scans to track the deployment of two email authentication technologies: \textbf{SPF} (Sender Policy Framework) and \textbf{DMARC} (Domain-based Message Authentication, Reporting \& Conformance).

Owners of \textbf{.gov domains} should make a plan to implement SPF, DKIM, or DomainKeys Identified Mail (if the domain is used for mail-sending), and DMARC, with a goal of setting a DMARC policy of ``reject". \textbf{This guidance also applies to all mail-sending hosts} on the domain.

\textbf{Setting a DMARC policy of ``reject" provides the strongest protection} against spoofed email, ensuring that unauthenticated messages are rejected at the mail server, even before delivery. Attaining this status in the complex email architectures common in the federal government will require coordination by agency technical leadership.

Specific recommendations can be found in individual agency ``Trustworthy Email Reports", which, among other resources, culls suggested actions from \href{http://nvlpubs.nist.gov/nistpubs/SpecialPublications/NIST.SP.800-177.pdf}{\underline{NIST SP 800-177}} and a March 2017 \href{https://www.ftc.gov/system/files/documents/reports/businesses-can-help-stop-phishing-protect-their-brands-using-email-authentication-ftc-staff/email_authentication_staff_perspective.pdf}{\underline{FTC report}} on email authentication.

